text=:Category: Varia%0a:Essential: {Category.Varia$:essential}%0a:Title: A Link From Turkey to Korea%0a:Author: vincent_c%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 07.05.2021 - 17:19%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210508-201754-653020#%0a* [-08.05.2021 - 13:17-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210508-201754-653020#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a#foxbegin 210508-201749-979630#%0a----%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-08.05.2021 - 13:17-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a!!!!!TA_lili%0aThere exists controversy about the Altaic hypothesis within the CMU linguistics program! I can't say who believes in it though... %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210508-201749-979630 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a#foxend 210508-201749-979630#%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA look into the similarities between Turkish and Korean (and Japanese)%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe first time I had ever heard that Turkish and Korean were languages that were similar, I was confused because the two countries seemed quite far apart and culturally unrelated to each other. I had been told this by a waiter, while eating at a restaurant with a Korean friend, as he knew many people from back home in Turkey who were learning Korean due to its similarity to Turkish.%0a%0aOn the surface level, Turkish and Korean (and Japanese) are subject object verb languages, and represent morphological and syntactical functions through affixation. %0a%0aSome other similarities also emerge though. The languages have a grammatical restriction on adding a plural suffix to a noun if the noun is given a quantifier. Nominative personal pronouns can be added to give emphatic emphasis. For example "Ben Japon'um" is an emphatic "Japon'um", meaning I am Japanese,  and similar sentences with similar emphatic emphasis can be recreated in Japanese and Korean.%0a%0aSome linguists have proposed that these three languages are part of a sprachbund called Altaic. A sprachbund is a group of languages that share some features due to geographical proximity. However the Altaic sprachbund is controversial, as other linguists believe that the similarities are converging, rather than diverging from a shared root. %0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://www.jstor.org/stable/41927271%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sprachbund%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
