diff:1620433143:1620433143:=1,55d0%0a%3c :Category: Varia%0a%3c :Essential: {Category.Varia$:essential}%0a%3c :Title: A Link From Turkey to Korea%0a%3c :Author: vincent_c%0a%3c :Section: C%0a%3c :Completed: 07.05.2021 - 17:19%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c A look into the similarities between Turkish and Korean (and Japanese)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c The first time I had ever heard that Turkish and Korean were languages that were similar, I was confused because the two countries seemed quite far apart and culturally unrelated to each other. I had been told this by a waiter, while eating at a restaurant with a Korean friend, as he knew many people from back home in Turkey who were learning Korean due to its similarity to Turkish.%0a%3c %0a%3c On the surface level, Turkish and Korean (and Japanese) are subject object verb languages, and represent morphological and syntactical functions through affixation. %0a%3c %0a%3c Some other similarities also emerge though. The languages have a grammatical restriction on adding a plural suffix to a noun if the noun is given a quantifier. Nominative personal pronouns can be added to give emphatic emphasis. For example "Ben Japon'um" is an emphatic "Japon'um", meaning I am Japanese,  and similar sentences with similar emphatic emphasis can be recreated in Japanese and Korean.%0a%3c %0a%3c Some linguists have proposed that these three languages are part of a sprachbund called Altaic. A sprachbund is a group of languages that share some features due to geographical proximity. However the Altaic sprachbund is controversial, as other linguists believe that the similarities are converging, rather than diverging from a shared root. %0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://www.jstor.org/stable/41927271%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sprachbund%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
